1.3 Report Generation Flow (Step-by-Step)
Step 1: Admin selects report options

(UI)

Report Type: Classroom Report
Date Range: This Month

Step 2: Frontend sends API request
POST /api/reports/generate
{
  "type": "classroom",
  "dateRange": "this_month"
}

Step 3: Backend applies business logic

Example: Attendance Report

Fetch attendance records

SELECT student_id, date, status
FROM attendance
WHERE date BETWEEN startDate AND endDate;


Calculate:

Total present days

Total absent days

Attendance percentage

This matches your system goal:

No fake or dummy data, only real records.

Step 4: Report formatting

Backend converts data into:

Structured table

Summary section

Then generates:

PDF file (recommended for academic projects)

Libraries (example):

Node.js → pdfkit

Laravel → dompdf

Step 5: Save report history
INSERT INTO report_logs
(report_type, date_range, generated_by, file_path)
VALUES (...)


This is why Recent Reports appears automatically.

Step 6: UI updates “Recent Reports”

Frontend fetches:

GET /api/reports/recent


And displays:

Attendance Report – June 2023

Financial Summary – Q2 2023

Student Progress – May 2023

1.4 Download Report (UI → Backend)

When admin clicks Download:

GET /api/reports/download/{report_id}


Backend:

Verifies admin role

Returns PDF file

🔐 Security Rule
Only admin can access all reports.

1.5 How to Write This in Chapter 4 (Ready-to-Use)

“The report generation module allows administrators to generate dynamic reports such as attendance, classroom, student progress, and financial summaries. Reports are generated based on real-time data retrieved from the system database using selected filters such as report type and date range. Once generated, reports are stored as downloadable PDF files and logged in the system for future reference under the Recent Reports section.”

